---

## Context

aidemd.dev is a static documentation site (Next.js 16 with `output: "export"`, deployed to GitHub Pages) for the AIDE methodology. Today the site renders eight canonical docs under `/docs/*` and a landing page at `/`. The sitemap, robots.txt, and root layout JSON-LD exist but only cover those pages. The site is missing three entire artifact categories that `aide_init` installs into every project: nine pipeline agents, twelve commands, and two skills. Those artifacts have no rendered pages, no metadata, no sitemap entries, and no presence in any LLM-readable file. A searcher looking for "aide architect agent" finds nothing on aidemd.dev; an LLM asked about any AIDE command has no first-party source to cite.

The docs index currently lists only the `.aide/` canonical docs. It does not surface the `.claude/` folder at all, which means agents, commands, and skills are invisible both to visitors browsing the site and to crawlers indexing it. The site also has no `llms.txt` file, so LLMs cannot programmatically discover the full artifact inventory.

Key constraints: static export means no server-side rendering — canonical tags must be injected client-side. All dynamic routes require `generateStaticParams` to pre-render at build time. The site's voice is precise and engineering-credible; marketing language is prohibited by the parent spec.

## Strategy

**Page inventory.** Create individual rendered pages for every artifact in the `aide_init` scaffold: nine agent pages (`/agents/aide-spec-writer`, `/agents/aide-architect`, etc.), twelve command pages (`/commands/aide`, `/commands/aide-spec`, etc.), and two skill pages (`/skills/study-playbook`, `/skills/brain`). Content for each page is sourced from the local files that `aide_init` installs: `.claude/agents/aide/*.md`, `.claude/commands/aide/*.md`, and `.claude/skills/*/SKILL.md`. This directly serves the outcome requiring every leaf node in the scaffold tree to link to its own rendered page.

**Docs index as scaffold tree.** Replace the current docs index with a file-tree view that mirrors a freshly bootstrapped project. The tree shows two top-level folders — `.aide/` containing the canonical docs plus the intent template, and `.claude/` containing `agents/aide/` (nine agents), `commands/aide/` (twelve commands), and `skills/` (two skills). No `.zed/` folder appears. Every leaf in the tree is a link to its rendered page. This layout lets a visitor browse the site the way they would browse a project on disk, which is the core metaphor the intent requires.

**Title tag pattern.** Use the format `{Concept Name} -- AIDE: Autonomous Intent-Driven Engineering` for all interior pages. Specific titles:
- Homepage: `AIDE: Autonomous Intent-Driven Engineering -- Code is ephemeral. Intent is law.`
- Spec page: `AIDE Spec -- Autonomous Intent-Driven Engineering Methodology`
- Progressive Disclosure: `Progressive Disclosure -- AIDE Methodology for Agent-Readable Code`
- Agent pages follow the same pattern: `AIDE Architect -- AIDE: Autonomous Intent-Driven Engineering`
- Command pages: `aide:build -- AIDE: Autonomous Intent-Driven Engineering`
- Skill pages: `study-playbook -- AIDE: Autonomous Intent-Driven Engineering`
Every title is unique. No two pages share a title. This guards against the undesired outcome of near-duplicate SERP snippets.

**Meta description pattern.** Each description is 140-160 characters, includes "AIDE", and reads like a dictionary definition an LLM could extract — not a marketing pitch. Specific examples:
- Homepage: "AIDE (Autonomous Intent-Driven Engineering) is a software methodology where intent specs cascade through a pipeline of specialized AI agents to produce production-quality code."
- Spec page: "The AIDE spec (.aide file) is a structured intent contract that governs a code module -- defining scope, intent, desired outcomes, and failure modes for AI agent pipelines."
- Progressive Disclosure: "Progressive disclosure structures code in tiers -- folder tree, JSDoc, inline comments -- so AI agents stop at the shallowest layer that answers their question."
Every other doc, agent, command, and skill page gets a similarly precise description written in the same definitional voice. Descriptions must not repeat the same sentence template with only the artifact name swapped in — each one must reflect what that specific artifact does.

**Canonical URLs.** Every page declares `<link rel="canonical" href="https://aidemd.dev/{path}">`. Because the site uses `output: "export"` (static), use a client-side `CanonicalTag` component mounted once in the root layout that reads `usePathname()` and injects the canonical link tag via `useEffect`. This is the confirmed pattern for static exports per the coding playbook's SEO conventions — `alternates.canonical` in `generateMetadata` is unreliable for static exports.

**Open Graph tags.** Handled via `generateMetadata` (or `metadata` constant for static pages). Every page sets:
- `og:title` — same as the title tag
- `og:description` — same as the meta description
- `og:url` — same as the canonical URL
- `og:type` — `"website"` for the homepage and docs index, `"article"` for all doc, agent, command, and skill pages
- `og:site_name` — `"AIDE"`
No separate OG component is needed; Next.js injects OG tags from the metadata API output.

**JSON-LD structured data.** Two tiers, per the playbook pattern:
- Root layout: Organization schema (`name: "AIDEMD"`, `url: "https://aidemd.dev"`) and WebSite schema. These are already in place.
- Per-page: Each doc, agent, command, and skill page carries a TechArticle schema. TechArticle is chosen over SoftwareApplication because these pages document concepts and processes, not downloadable tools. The schema includes:
  - `headline`: the page title
  - `description`: the meta description
  - `url`: the canonical URL
  - `datePublished`: sourced from actual content dates, not fabricated
  - `author`: `{ "@type": "Organization", "name": "TetsuKodai Group LLC" }`
  - `publisher`: `{ "@type": "Organization", "name": "TetsuKodai Group LLC", "url": "https://tetsukod.ai" }`
Place per-page schemas in the page component using `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` with a unique `id` attribute to prevent duplicate injection. This guards against the undesired outcome of fabricated structured data — every field must trace to actual content.

**robots.txt.** The existing `robots.ts` route handler already produces the correct output: `User-agent: *`, `Allow: /`, `Sitemap: https://aidemd.dev/sitemap.xml`. No changes needed.

**sitemap.xml.** Extend the existing `sitemap.ts` route handler to include all new pages: nine agent URLs, twelve command URLs, and two skill URLs, in addition to the existing homepage, docs index, and doc page entries. Use `<lastmod>` dates. No page may be omitted from the sitemap.

**llms.txt.** Serve an `llms.txt` file at the site root. Use a route handler (e.g., `src/app/llms.txt/route.ts`) that returns `text/plain` content. The file follows the emerging llms.txt convention with sections for Core Concepts, Agents, Commands, Skills, Key Terms, Install, and Publisher. Every entry includes a URL and a description sufficient for an LLM to answer "what does X do?" from the file alone. The exact content structure:

```
# AIDE -- Autonomous Intent-Driven Engineering

> AIDE is a software development methodology that puts intent at the center of engineering. Short .aide spec files live next to the code they govern, forming a cascading intent tree. A pipeline of eight specialized AI agents -- spec writer, domain expert, strategist, architect, implementor, QA, aligner, auditor -- translates intent into production-quality software.

## Core Concepts
- AIDE Spec: https://aidemd.dev/docs/aide-spec
- AIDE Template: https://aidemd.dev/docs/aide-template
- Progressive Disclosure: https://aidemd.dev/docs/progressive-disclosure
- Cascading Alignment: https://aidemd.dev/docs/cascading-alignment
- Agent-Readable Code: https://aidemd.dev/docs/agent-readable-code
- Automated QA: https://aidemd.dev/docs/automated-qa
- Plan Spec: https://aidemd.dev/docs/plan-aide
- Todo Spec: https://aidemd.dev/docs/todo-aide

## Agents
- AIDE Spec Writer: https://aidemd.dev/agents/aide-spec-writer
- AIDE Domain Expert: https://aidemd.dev/agents/aide-domain-expert
- AIDE Strategist: https://aidemd.dev/agents/aide-strategist
- AIDE Architect: https://aidemd.dev/agents/aide-architect
- AIDE Implementor: https://aidemd.dev/agents/aide-implementor
- AIDE QA: https://aidemd.dev/agents/aide-qa
- AIDE Aligner: https://aidemd.dev/agents/aide-aligner
- AIDE Auditor: https://aidemd.dev/agents/aide-auditor
- AIDE Explorer: https://aidemd.dev/agents/aide-explorer

## Commands
- /aide: https://aidemd.dev/commands/aide
- /aide:spec: https://aidemd.dev/commands/aide-spec
- /aide:research: https://aidemd.dev/commands/aide-research
- /aide:synthesize: https://aidemd.dev/commands/aide-synthesize
- /aide:plan: https://aidemd.dev/commands/aide-plan
- /aide:build: https://aidemd.dev/commands/aide-build
- /aide:qa: https://aidemd.dev/commands/aide-qa
- /aide:fix: https://aidemd.dev/commands/aide-fix
- /aide:refactor: https://aidemd.dev/commands/aide-refactor
- /aide:align: https://aidemd.dev/commands/aide-align
