## Skills
- study-playbook: https://aidemd.dev/skills/study-playbook
- brain: https://aidemd.dev/skills/brain

## Key Terms
- .aide file: A structured intent spec (scope, intent, outcomes, strategy) that lives next to the code it governs.
- Intent tree: The hierarchy of .aide specs from project root to deepest module, where each child narrows its parent's intent.
- Progressive disclosure: Code structured in tiers (folder tree, JSDoc, inline comments) so agents read only the depth they need.
- Cascading alignment: Parent intent flows down the tree; child specs inherit and narrow, never contradict.
- Brain: A persistent external knowledge store (Obsidian vault, MCP memory) holding domain research and engineering conventions.
- Fix loop: QA produces a todo.aide, implementor fixes one item per session in clean context, QA re-validates.

## Install
npx @aidemd-mcp/server@latest

## Publisher
TetsuKodai Group LLC -- https://tetsukod.ai
```

Each agent, command, and skill entry should also include a brief inline description (following the URL) so the llms.txt satisfies the outcome requiring an LLM to answer questions from the file alone.

**Static route generation.** All new dynamic routes (agents, commands, skills) require `generateStaticParams` since the site uses `output: "export"`. Use the hardcoded-list variant — all slugs are known at build time.

**Semantic HTML.** New page templates must use `<article>` for artifact content, `<nav>` for the scaffold tree, `<section>` with `aria-label` for thematic groupings, and `<time>` for dates. The scaffold tree on the docs index should use `<nav aria-label="Scaffold tree">` wrapping a nested list structure.

**Build order.** Follow the playbook's feature build order: types first (structured data shapes, page metadata types), then data sources (slug lists, content loaders for agents/commands/skills), then route handlers (extend sitemap, add llms.txt route), then components (CanonicalTag, JSON-LD injection), then pages (new dynamic routes with generateMetadata and generateStaticParams), then audit (ARIA, semantic HTML, OG verification).

## Good examples

**Correct title tag (agent page):**
`AIDE Architect -- AIDE: Autonomous Intent-Driven Engineering`

**Correct title tag (command page):**
`aide:build -- AIDE: Autonomous Intent-Driven Engineering`

**Correct meta description (spec page):**
"The AIDE spec (.aide file) is a structured intent contract that governs a code module -- defining scope, intent, desired outcomes, and failure modes for AI agent pipelines."

**Correct meta description (agent page):**
"The AIDE architect agent reads a strategy spec and brain research, then produces a step-by-step plan.aide that the implementor executes without further design decisions."

**Correct JSON-LD for a doc page:**
```json
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "TechArticle",
  "headline": "Progressive Disclosure -- AIDE Methodology for Agent-Readable Code",
  "description": "Progressive disclosure structures code in tiers -- folder tree, JSDoc, inline comments -- so AI agents stop at the shallowest layer that answers their question.",
  "url": "https://aidemd.dev/docs/progressive-disclosure",
  "datePublished": "2026-04-11",
  "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "TetsuKodai Group LLC" },
  "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "TetsuKodai Group LLC", "url": "https://tetsukod.ai" }
}
```

**Correct Open Graph tags (doc page):**
```
og:title = "Progressive Disclosure -- AIDE Methodology for Agent-Readable Code"
og:description = "Progressive disclosure structures code in tiers..."
og:url = "https://aidemd.dev/docs/progressive-disclosure"
og:type = "article"
og:site_name = "AIDE"
```

**Correct llms.txt agent entry (with description):**
`- AIDE Architect: https://aidemd.dev/agents/aide-architect -- Reads strategy specs and brain research, produces a step-by-step plan.aide for the implementor.`

**Correct scaffold tree structure on docs index:**
```
.aide/
  aide-spec.md          -> /docs/aide-spec
  aide-template.md      -> /docs/aide-template
  plan-aide.md          -> /docs/plan-aide
